Ubisoft reported its financial performance for the first half of 2024-25, with €642.3 million in net bookings, marking a 21.9% decline compared to the previous year. Digital bookings fell by 26.5%, and player recurring investments (PRI) dropped 39.2%. However, the back catalog demonstrated strength, with a 12% year-over-year increase, largely driven by games like Rainbow Six Siege and Assassin’s Creed, which retained significant engagement.

Despite sales misses and a 36% drop in Q2 IFRS sales compared to last year, Ubisoft reached positive engagement figures, with monthly active users (MAUs) rising 3% year-over-year to 37 million. Ubisoft's Rainbow Six Siege and Assassin’s Creed each attracted over 30 million unique active users, contributing to Ubisoft's long-term portfolio value. Ubisoft maintains its FY25 targets for approximately €1.95 billion in net bookings and a break-even in non-IFRS operating income, despite lower-than-expected performance in Star Wars Outlaws.

Ubisoft's ongoing cost reduction efforts have resulted in €200 million in annualized savings, reducing employee numbers by over 2,000. With cash flow improvements and further strategic asset sales under consideration, Ubisoft aims to enhance cash generation, focusing on core areas like open-world and live-service games.

Ubisoft Entertainment has officially released its first blockchain game, "Champions Tactics: Grimoria Chronicles." The game is a tactical NFT battler that launched on PC and features a free-to-start model, allowing players to engage in battles using unique figurines. These figurines, which are NFTs, can be purchased with in-game gold or cryptocurrency, and their prices range from $7 to $64,000. 

The game pits players against each other in turn-based battles using squads.

just download the pdf file, copy it into chat gpt to give a summary. No need to listen to the whole call

Ubisoft reported its financial performance for the first half of 2024-25, with €642.3 million in net bookings, marking a 21.9% decline compared to the previous year. Digital bookings fell by 26.5%, and player recurring investments (PRI) dropped 39.2%. However, the back catalog demonstrated strength, with a 12% year-over-year increase, largely driven by games like Rainbow Six Siege and Assassin’s Creed, which retained significant engagement.

Despite sales misses and a 36% drop in Q2 IFRS sales compared to last year, Ubisoft reached positive engagement figures, with monthly active users (MAUs) rising 3% year-over-year to 37 million. Ubisoft's Rainbow Six Siege and Assassin’s Creed each attracted over 30 million unique active users, contributing to Ubisoft's long-term portfolio value. Ubisoft maintains its FY25 targets for approximately €1.95 billion in net bookings and a break-even in non-IFRS operating income, despite lower-than-expected performance in Star Wars Outlaws.

Ubisoft's ongoing cost reduction efforts have resulted in €200 million in annualized savings, reducing employee numbers by over 2,000. With cash flow improvements and further strategic asset sales under consideration, Ubisoft aims to enhance cash generation, focusing on core areas like open-world and live-service games.
